<h2 class="section-heading">Hello, Nao! </h2>
<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;骏马腾飞春来报，梅花绽放祝福道。转眼已是马年，期间做了些水水的项目，写了些水水的paper，重要的是家人团聚过大年。回来的第一个周，就来参加Nao的机器人创客马拉松。不同于之前参加的Hackathon，这次由于是基于特定机器人Nao开发，所以之前还有一个基础的培训。这里我就从培训开始写起，做一次全程的记录。</p>

<h2 class="section-heading">3月18日 － 基本功能和API</h2>
<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Nao (pronounced now) is an autonomous, programmable humanoid robot developed by Aldebaran Robotics, a French robotics company headquartered in Paris. The robot's development began with the launch of Project Nao in 2004. On 15 August 2007, Nao replaced Sony's robot dog Aibo as the robot used in the RoboCup Standard Platform League (SPL), an international robot soccer competition. The Nao was used in RoboCup 2008 and 2009, and the NaoV3R was chosen as the platform for the SPL at RoboCup 2010.</p>

<p>Owing to my Mac environment, I register and download the <a href="https://community.aldebaran.com/en/resources/software">Monitor</a>, which performs all the senser data of Nao including the vision and audio recognition API. Therefore, the Monitor offers the convenience of debug process. The first step of programming looks like <a href="">Labview</a>. Once the flow chart gets assured, the Python or C++ SDk make sense. </p>

<p>Python seems easier for me so the next step is to set the programming environment. The <a href="http://doc.aldebaran.com/2-1/dev/python/install_guide.html#python-install-guide">documentation for python shows the details. </a></p>